=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F9%2F24%29&utm_content=
=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F9%2F24%29&utm_medium=3D=
email_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

People may disagree on the specifics of a particular issue like trans right=
s, but I don=E2=80=99t think that they=E2=80=99re going to want to talk abo=
ut that in a way that=E2=80=99s bullying or cruel. What they=E2=80=99re rea=
lly saying is, Do you get us? Do you see us? Do you hear us? And you know w=
hat? If I were a steelworker=E2=80=99s family in Pennsylvania, or an autowo=
rker=E2=80=99s family in Ohio, or a family of carpenters, and I watched the=
 Democratic National Convention this year, I don=E2=80=99t know that I woul=
d feel seen. The fact we didn=E2=80=99t have [Teamsters president] Sean O=
=E2=80=99Brien speak at the D.N.C.=E2=80=94who made that decision?

The DOGE Question

You said a few days ago you want to work with Elon Musk and Vivek Ramaswamy=
 on DOGE, and find some ways to cut government spending or inefficiencies. =
Have you talked to Elon Musk directly about this? And what are some areas o=
f agreement you could come to with them as a Democrat?

I=E2=80=99ve known Elon for 15 years. I=E2=80=99ve texted back and forth wi=
th him, and I=E2=80=99ve talked to him on and off for years. One thing to p=
oint out: Obama helped Elon disrupt the defense industry when it came to th=
e rocket launches. Boeing had a monopoly with Lockheed Martin on launching =
rockets to put satellites up in space, and Ash Carter and Barack Obama said=
, Elon, you can do it cheaper? Fine. We=E2=80=99re going to let you bid. He=
 had rockets that were reusable, [which is] the way he underbid Boeing and =
Lockheed. And today, the American
taxpayers have saved money because of Obama=E2=80=99s collaboration with El=
on Musk and getting SpaceX to do that.

So the opposite of what Biden did by stiff-arming Elon and Tesla on that E.=
V. summit.

Biden should have invited him. I don=E2=80=99t understand why he didn=E2=80=
=99t. When Obama gave the E.V. loan to Tesla, we should have insisted on la=
bor neutrality in that loan. We didn=E2=80=99t, and that was a miss. I=E2=
=80=99m for Tesla allowing unionization, and Elon knows that. He knows we h=
ave a disagreement. But you don=E2=80=99t disinvite him; you invite him and=
 you make the case. You don=E2=80=99t say, like Biden did, that [General Mo=
tors C.E.O.] Mary Barra started the electric vehicle revolution. That would=
 be like saying that Isaac Newton didn=E2=80=99t start calculus or somethin=
g. I mean, it=E2=80=99s just wrong! So I think that was gratuitously insult=
ing.

With DOGE, what I would look for is where we can get rid of the grip of the=
 five aerospace and
defense primes, and help make the defense department more efficient. Let=E2=
=80=99s get rid of some of the excess profits of defense contractors. That =
would be enormous. It=E2=80=99s 56 percent of the budget! Or, what if they =
come up with a way to automatically populate tax returns? That would be gre=
at. That=E2=80=99s an idea Democrats have been pushing. The point is to sup=
port policies where they will help the American people and oppose them wher=
e they won=E2=80=99t. If they go after Social Security, obviously I=E2=80=
=99ll oppose that with every fiber of my being. We should be for increasing=
 Social Security benefits. Or if they try to dismantle funding for the C.F.=
P.B., I would oppose that completely. The C.F.P.B. is saving money for many=
 consumers with credit card fees and mortgage fees.

So let=E2=80=99s not just reflexively oppose making government more efficie=
nt. If they=E2=80=99re going after agencies that are genuinely duplicative =
and there=E2=80=99s waste, then we should be forward-looking at that.
F.D.R. in his New Deal speech said, we don=E2=80=99t want wasteful governme=
nt spending. Obama talked about that. What Bernie says is, we=E2=80=99re sp=
ending money, not wasting money. We have to show that government can be eff=
ective, and also that we=E2=80=99re the party that=E2=80=99s willing to cut=
 wasteful spending.

Last thing, what=E2=80=99s the next step for you? You are a unique voice, a=
t least right now. What do you want to do if you don=E2=80=99t see a voice =
like this in the Democratic primary in four years? Would you run?

You=E2=80=99re basically asking the president question in a different way.

Yeah, duh.

I want to build the economic platform, not just for the Democratic Party, b=
ut for the country. My father came to this country in 1968, to Michigan, an=
d it was the time when we were about to go to the moon. America was the pla=
ce to do big things. It was a country that was the manufacturing and techno=
logy superpower of the world. We had this vibrant
middle class. I want that vision for America where the technology we have, =
in A.I. and biotechnology, doesn=E2=80=99t just help a few zip codes. That =
we mobilize all of our people to be the best manufacturer in the world, to =
have economic vitality in every part of the country.

I believe that I have studied enough American history and talked to enough =
people in communities to have a concrete solution of how we do that. I also=
 know some of the extraordinary people who are working on those things to b=
ring that vision to life. And whoever ends up being in positions of power, =
I=E2=80=99d say, please plagiarize my ideas. I want this platform to succee=
d. It=E2=80=99s fundamentally what I think the country needs, and what role=
 I will have in all of that is=E2=80=A6 who knows? That=E2=80=99s for peopl=
e to decide.

