             <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><b>You represent=
 part of the Bay Area, the kind of affluent, highly educated place that vot=
ed for Kamala Harris. How do you explain the Trump voter to someone in Cupe=
rtino or Sunnyvale, who doesn=E2=80=99t understand why someone would vote f=
or him?</b><br/><br/>I have a message both for people with advanced degrees=
 in Cupertino and also the folks who have lost some of these industrial job=
s. Let me start with the people in Cupertino. I would say to them, you can=
=E2=80=99t have a country where we have $12 trillion in our district=E2=80=
=94$12 trillion of market value producing more wealth in one zip code than =
has probably ever been produced in the history of humanity=E2=80=94and in o=
ther parts of America, people feel that life was better off 50 years ago, t=
hat they don=E2=80=99t have as good paying jobs, and that if you only have =
a high school degree, your real income has fallen
by 22 percent. They are struggling with healthcare costs and childcare cost=
s and education costs. That=E2=80=99s a recipe for division, for resentment=
, for anger. We have to tackle inequality in America=E2=80=94geographic ine=
quality, class inequality, inequality in all its dimensions=E2=80=94to brin=
g this nation together to have a common purpose. Tackling inequality isn=E2=
=80=99t about redistribution; it=E2=80=99s giving people the opportunity to=
 participate in contributing to the economy and building wealth. <br/><br/>=
<b>Now, what would you say to the people in the deindustrialized regions?</=
b><br/><br/>I=E2=80=99d say don=E2=80=99t bash higher education. You want m=
odern factories? Okay, well, you=E2=80=99re going to need the Ph.D.s, you=
=E2=80=99re going to need the college graduates. You=E2=80=99re blatantly l=
ying to people if you think we=E2=80=99re going to bring new factories and =
new industries and new economic revitalization to these communities while a=
lso bashing higher education. What we need in this country is both. We need=
 the
Ph.D.s and the scientists and the engineers=E2=80=94and also the electricia=
ns and the plumbers and the skilled trades and people who have a pathway fo=
r contributing extraordinary value without a college degree. I don=E2=80=99=
t agree with the demagogic bashing of higher education, but I also think th=
at we shouldn=E2=80=99t have a 400-to-1 differential, where the government =
spends $400 on college education as opposed to building all the other trade=
s and skills we=E2=80=99re going to need to have a successful economy. <br/=
><br/><b>On the culture front, what is the right answer to those ads Trump =
ran about Harris and transgender surgeries, basically saying I=E2=80=99m fo=
r you and she=E2=80=99s not? How do you make the argument that Democrats ar=
en=E2=80=99t just about identity politics and pronouns and elite cultural a=
ttitudes? </b><br/><br/>Most of the Americans I grew up with in Bucks Count=
y, Pennsylvania, don=E2=80=99t like punching down. I don=E2=80=99t think th=
ose ads that are picking on someone, or picking on a community,
reflect what is true about the American spirit. I think what Americans are =
concerned about is, do Democrats understand what they=E2=80=99ve gone throu=
gh? Do Democrats understand that they have been going generation after gene=
ration with a decline in their security and in their stability? Do we under=
stand their contribution to America? That they helped build America? Their =
kids fight in the wars, their parents or grandparents scaled the cliffs of =
Normandy. They built the steel. They built the energy. They built the econo=
my that allows us to succeed. And now they feel discarded. <br/></td>
